⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Question 107/120 – Handling Data Skew

🎤 Interview Question

One department ("IT") contains 90% of the records, while the remaining departments have very few records.

The join is extremely slow.

How would you handle this?


---

✅ Recommended Solution

Common approaches include:

Broadcast the small table (if applicable).

Use key salting for heavily skewed keys.

Enable AQE to split skewed partitions automatically.


Example (AQE):

spark.conf.set(
    "spark.sql.adaptive.skewJoin.enabled",
    "true"
)


---

🎤 Most Asked Interview Questions

Q1. What is data skew?

Answer

Data skew occurs when one or a few keys contain a disproportionate amount of data, causing uneven workload across executors.


---

Q2. What problems does skew cause?

Answer

Long-running tasks

Poor cluster utilization

Slow joins and aggregations



---

Q3. How can skew be reduced?

Answer

Broadcast joins

Key salting

AQE skew join optimization

Better partitioning strategy



---

⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Question 108/120 – Spark UI & Job Debugging

🎤 Interview Question

A Spark job takes much longer than expected.

How would you use the Spark UI to investigate the issue?


---

✅ Recommended Solution

Inspect the following Spark UI tabs:

Jobs → Overall job status

Stages → Identify slow stages

Tasks → Find skewed or failed tasks

SQL → Analyze execution plans

Storage → Verify cached DataFrames

Executors → Monitor memory and CPU usage



---

🎤 Most Asked Interview Questions

Q1. Which Spark UI tab helps identify slow tasks?

Answer

The Stages and Tasks tabs.


---

Q2. What symptoms indicate data skew?

Answer

One or a few tasks take much longer than all others in the same stage.


---

Q3. What information does the Storage tab provide?

Answer

It shows cached and persisted DataFrames along with their memory and disk usage.


